Pulsatile Ô¨Çow in model cerebral aneurysms
Julia Mikhala,‚àó, Bernard J. Geurtsa,b
a Multiscale

Modeling and Simulation, Dept. of Applied Mathematics, University of Twente, P.O. Box 217, 7500 AE Enschede, The Netherlands
Turbulence, Dept. of Applied Physics, Eindhoven University of Technology, P.O. Box 513, 5600 MB Eindhoven, The Netherlands

b Anisotropic

Abstract
We present an immersed boundary method based on volume penalization, with which pulsatile Ô¨Çow in a model
cerebral aneurysm is simulated. The model aneurysm consists of a curved vessel merged with a spherical cavity. The
dominant vortical structures arising in the time-dependent Ô¨Çow are discussed and the evolution of the maximal shear
stress in the aneurysm is analyzed. We approximate Ô¨Çow properties of blood by those of an incompressible Newtonian
Ô¨Çuid. The Ô¨Çow inside the aneurysm is simulated with the use of a skew-symmetric Ô¨Ånite-volume discretization and
explicit time-stepping. We focus on eÔ¨Äects due to variations in the amplitude of the pulsatile Ô¨Çow as well as due to
changes in the Reynolds number (Re) by studying Ô¨Çow at Re = 100, 250 and 500. At Re = 500 a complex timedependence in the shear stress levels is observed, reÔ¨Çecting the lively development of the Ô¨Çow in the model aneurysm
in which vortices are created continuously inside the curved vessel and in the spherical cavity of the aneurysm. An
increase in the amplitude of the pulsatile Ô¨Çow increases the shear stress levels somewhat, but at Re = 500 the Ô¨Çow is
mainly dominated by its intrinsic unsteadiness. Reducing the Reynolds number yields a stronger contribution of the
periodic pulsatile Ô¨Çow forcing: at Re = 100 we Ô¨Ånd a strong dominance of shear stress levels due to the forcing, while
at Re = 250 the intrinsic and pulsatile unsteadiness are of comparable importance.
Keywords:
cerebral aneurysm, pulsatile Ô¨Çow, immersed boundary method, volume-penalization, incompressible Ô¨Çow, shear
stress

1. Introduction
There is a growing medical need to obtain predictions of the Ô¨Çow behavior and shear stresses inside the human
brain that is speciÔ¨Åc to individual patients. The prediction of the Ô¨Çow constitutes a challenging and timely computational multiscale modeling problem, aimed at understanding and identifying the likelihood of long-time rupture from
an analysis of short-time pulsatile Ô¨Çow [13]. Understanding such pulsatile Ô¨Çow patterns will help to describe longtime accumulation eÔ¨Äects such as the growth of an aneurysm, or the deterioration of the vessel wall due to reduced
blood circulation. This capability allows also a more complete planning of surgical intervention and can be used to
predict the eÔ¨Äectiveness of such procedures. A huge amount of work has been done on Computational Fluid Dynamics
(CFD) of Ô¨Çow in the human brain and in the cardiovascular system [11, 2, 1, 12, 6, 3]. The most commonly adopted
numerical approach is the Ô¨Ånite element method. This method can, in principle, represent highly complex geometries but at considerable expense, particularly when dealing with raw biomedical imagery to deÔ¨Åne vessel geometries
