2. Numerical method
In this section we introduce the Ô¨Çuid-mechanical model that is used to simulate blood Ô¨Çow in cerebral aneurysms.
The numerical method employs a volume-penalization immersed boundary (IB) method, which is brieÔ¨Çy reviewed
and illustrated for the geometry of a curved blood vessel. For viscous Ô¨Çow at Reynolds number Re = 1 we present
convergence Ô¨Åndings achieved by grid reÔ¨Ånement.
There is a number of diÔ¨Äerent approaches to model Ô¨Çow of blood in the human brain. A comprehensive overview
is given in [12]. One way is to approximate blood as a simple Newtonian Ô¨Çuid with constant viscosity [2]. More
reÔ¨Åned models include the shear-thinning behavior of blood by adopting, e.g., the Carreau-Yasuda model to capture
non-Newtonian rheology [1, 6]. Under physiological Ô¨Çow conditions in suÔ¨Éciently large arteries the non-Newtonian
corrections were found to be quite small [11, 3]. The main Ô¨Çow features were the same as in Newtonian Ô¨Çow,
albeit at somewhat diÔ¨Äerent stress and velocity levels. In this paper we study to what extent an immersed boundary
method is suitable to simulate time-dependent Ô¨Çow in the circle of Willis; for these low Reynolds Ô¨Çows in larger
cerebral vessels non-Newtonian corrections are neglected. Hence, we restrict to incompressible Newtonian Ô¨Çuid
mechanics as represented by the Navier-Stokes equations. The total physical domain Œ© consists of a Ô¨Çuid part Œ© f and
a complementary solid part Œ© s . The interface between the two will be identiÔ¨Åed as ‚àÇŒ© f at which the no-slip condition
applies. The governing equations, completed with a no-slip boundary condition on the solid walls of the domain are
given in non-dimensional form by:
