part Œ© f the masking function H(x) = 0. Correspondingly, around such a location the regular Navier-Stokes system in
(1)-(2) is employed. For any location inside the solid part Œ© s of the domain the masking function H takes the value
1. Since Œµ is chosen very small, the forcing inside the solid domain dominates all other Ô¨Çuxes in the Navier-Stokes
equations.
The form of the forcing f inside the solid part implies that the velocity component u is negligible; if at some
location in the solid u would, for some reason, have become non-zero then the forcing drives the local velocity
exponentially quickly back to negligible values. In the region near the interface between the solid and the Ô¨Çuid parts
of the domain the velocity Ô¨Åeld would be forced to negligible values within a very thin strip of the grid. A suÔ¨Éciently
small value of Œµ will imply a very localized region in which a non-trivial Ô¨Çow in Œ© f connects to a solution with
negligible values in Œ© s . This rough sketch identiÔ¨Åes that the simple volume forcing (4) can indeed approximate a noslip boundary condition, localized to within one grid cell. Thus, accurate results can in principle be achieved provided
the spatial resolution is adequate.
Numerically the equations resulting from the introduction of the forcing (4) in the Navier-Stokes equations are
treated with a Ô¨Ånite-volume discretization where the skew-symmetry of the nonlinear convective Ô¨Çuxes and the
positive-deÔ¨Ånite dissipative nature of the viscous Ô¨Çuxes are preserved [14]. This method can be shown to be stable on any (coarse) resolution, with a proper treating of a small scale details in a numerical solution. In order to
capture forces on the solid walls of the domain the treatment of the small near-wall Ô¨Çow structures is essential. A
second order accurate method for the Ô¨Çuxes is employed, implemented on a staggered grid. The eÔ¨Äect of these Ô¨Çuxes
is integrated in time using an explicit time-stepping algorithm of Adams-Bashforth type [14]. The contribution of
the forcing term f is integrated implicitly in time, which overcomes severe stability problems that would arise with
explicit methods as Œµ
1. The total computational domain is endowed with periodic boundary conditions. In order
to generate a non-trivial Ô¨Çow we impose a time-dependent pressure drop across the streamwise direction x, chosen
such that the desired unsteady Ô¨Çow-rate is maintained. In total, the pressure can be expressed at a(t)x + p where p(x, t)
denotes a periodic pressure Ô¨Åeld and a(t) is the time-dependent pressure gradient across the domain in the x direction.
The use of a staggered grid introduces the question how to deÔ¨Åne exactly the masking function. Intuitively, H
is easily deÔ¨Åned as indicated above. However, there is some freedom in its deÔ¨Ånition on grid-scale near a solidÔ¨Çuid interface. We work with an individual grid cell as the smallest elementary unit; this implies that a grid cell is
considered either as part of the solid or as part of the Ô¨Çuid. We need to identify on which component of the solution
to base the masking function as all three velocity components u, v, w and the pressure p are deÔ¨Åned on their respective
grids. We choose to work with H p , which means that if the center of a primary grid cell is in the Ô¨Çuid domain, then
the entire grid cell is deÔ¨Åned as part of Œ© f . This allows to deÔ¨Åne the precise location (within the resolution of the
adopted grid) of the solid-Ô¨Çuid interface in a ‚Äòstaircase‚Äô approximation. The convergence of the volume-penalization
IB method can be established on the basis of laminar Poiseuille Ô¨Çow in a straight cylindrical tube. This test-case was
considered in [8] and Ô¨Årst-order convergence was observed. This conÔ¨Årms results obtained for the plane channel Ô¨Çow
in case the no-slip condition is imposed within a grid cell of the solid wall [9].
