To illustrate the IB method for curved vessels we consider simple sinusoidal shapes for the centerline and a
constant circular cross-section in a plane locally normal to the tangent vector to the centerline. Simulations at Re = 1
as shown in Figure 1(a) clarify that the steady Ô¨Çow which develops closely follows the shape of the vessel. At each
location a well-deÔ¨Åned velocity proÔ¨Åle emerges as is seen in Figure 1(b). To illustrate the convergence of the method
for curved vessel we consider the pressure diÔ¨Äerence over the Ô¨Çow domain in the x-direction. The development of
this pressure diÔ¨Äerence at a number of spatial resolutions is displayed in Figure 2. We observe a clear convergence in
these pressure evolutions by comparing results obtained at N = 32, 64, 128 and 256. For longer simulation time all
these solutions converge to a steady state.
3. Reference pulsatile Ô¨Çow dynamics
In this section we consider the dynamics of pulsatile Ô¨Çow in a model aneurysm. First, we deÔ¨Åne the geometry
of the model aneurysm and motivate the adopted Ô¨Çow conditions. Subsequently, we analyze the velocity Ô¨Åeld and
shear forces for the reference case and compare the main characteristics as pressure drop and maximal shear stress for
pulsatile and constant mass Ô¨Çow rate which have the same average Ô¨Çow.
One of the common locations of cerebral aneurysms within the Circle of Willis is on the internal carotid artery
(ICA), where a typical mass Ô¨Çow rate is reported to be Q ‚âà 245ml/min [5]. The diameter of the ICA is of the
order of D ‚âà 0.42cm [7]. Together, this leads to a reference velocity U ‚âà 0.2947m/s and a corresponding Reynolds
number Re ‚âà 354 in which we used as reference kinematic viscosity ŒΩ = 3.5 ¬∑ 10‚àí6 m2 /s [12]. The natural variation in
conditions and geometry motivate to use Reynolds numbers in the general range of 100-500, properly including this
estimate obtained from literature.
The Reynolds number Re is the only parameter which is required to specify the Ô¨Çow conditions. It quantiÔ¨Åes the
ratio between the magnitude of the (destabilizing) convective transport u ¬∑ ‚àáu and the (stabilizing) viscous processes
‚àá2 u. It is well known that for relatively small Reynolds numbers Ô¨Çow is laminar and steady, which implies a smooth

816

Julia Mikhal et al. / Procedia Computer Science 4 (2011) 811‚Äì820

Figure 3: Three dimensional geometry of the model aneurysm that is constructed of a curved vessel and a spherical cavity attached to it.

velocity and pressure Ô¨Åeld at every moment in time. With increasing Reynolds number the Ô¨Çow can develop more
detailed vortical structures, e.g., associated with separated Ô¨Çow near relatively abrupt changes in the shape of a vessel.
A further increase in Re usually implies that the Ô¨Çow structures become unsteady with diÔ¨Äerent vortices. The range
of Reynolds numbers arising in the Ô¨Çow in the Circle of Willis, as estimated above, corresponds to laminar Ô¨Çow. As
point of reference we chose to work with Reynolds number Re = 500.
The Ô¨Çow domain is composed of a simple sinusoidally shaped cylindrical tube of radius R to which we add a
spherical cavity of radius 3R, thus arriving at a conÔ¨Åguration that generates signiÔ¨Åcant Ô¨Çow separation. As reference
length scale we adopt the basic radius R of the vessel. The geometry of the model aneurysm is based on a model for
curved blood vessel, which was described above in Section 2. The three dimensional geometry of the model aneurysm
is represented in Figure 3. The walls of the model aneurysm are assumed to be stationary in our studies reported here.
Further reÔ¨Ånements in which Ô¨Çow-structure interactions will be included are subject of current research.
The blood Ô¨Çow in a human body is pulsatile. Every person has their own complex heart beat characteristics. These
depend on all sorts of parameters [12]. One cardiac cycle consists of two phases: systole and diastole. Depending
on a stage the blood mass Ô¨Çow rate is higher or lower than average. In our investigations here we do not consider all
details of a real cardiac cycle, but concentrate on a simple sinusoidal pulsatile Ô¨Çow, representing a Fourier component
of the total cardiac pattern. We specify the average mass Ô¨Çow rate and add a sinusoidal perturbation for which the
amplitude and the frequency can be varied. As point of reference the amplitude of the sinusoidal pulse is taken 10%
of the average Ô¨Çow rate. The period of the oscillations is set to T = 20.
In Figure 4(a,b) we show the developing Ô¨Çow in the model aneurysm. Two snapshots of the unsteady Ô¨Çow are
plotted. The addition of a spherical cavity is seen to strongly aÔ¨Äect the Ô¨Çow in the curved vessel, which leads to
massive Ô¨Çow separation, e.g., from the rim of the spherical cavity. This produces a detached ‚Äòjet‚Äô that continuously
impinges on the wall of the cavity. The Ô¨Çow shows complex vortical structures that Ô¨Åll a large part of the spherical
cavity with recirculating Ô¨Çow. The occurrence of such Ô¨Çow structures contributes to an extension of the average
‚Äòresidence time‚Äô of blood inside the Ô¨Çow domain, expressing a deterioration of the quality of transport of nutrients to,
and waste products from the tissue surrounding the aneurysm. This can be an important indicator for the rate at which
health risks may develop.
The main challenge for the IB method in case of Ô¨Çow through model aneurysms is in capturing the Ô¨Çow near the
solid-Ô¨Çuid interface, which is required to compute the shear stress. We deÔ¨Åne the shear stress in terms of the gradient
of the velocity as follows. The rate of strain tensor S is such that
