4. Pressure drop and shear stress levels in pulsatile Ô¨Çow
In this section we consider the eÔ¨Äect of varying the forcing amplitude and the eÔ¨Äect of changing the Ô¨Çow conditions. These illustrate the Ô¨Çexibility and robustness with which the IB method can handle a range of dynamic
conditions.
In Figure 6 we show pressure drop and shear stress levels at Re = 500 and a range of amplitudes of the pulsatile
variations in the Ô¨Çow rate. The main signature of the pressure drop and the shear stress is the same as that observed in
Figure 5, the main diÔ¨Äerence being that an increase in the forcing amplitude leads to a somewhat stronger response in
the shear stress. As remarked earlier, at Re = 500 the intrinsic dynamics of the Ô¨Çow at the selected mean Ô¨Çow rate is
suÔ¨Éciently strong to overwhelm the eÔ¨Äects of the pulsatile Ô¨Çow as far as the shear stress is concerned.
We next present results for diÔ¨Äerent Reynolds numbers, Ô¨Åxing the amplitude of the pulsatile oscillations to 10%.
We consider Re = 100, 250 and 500. There are two, dynamically diÔ¨Äerent situations that correspond to these variations in the Reynolds number. If (situation A) we would keep the mass Ô¨Çow rate unchanged then a decrease in the
Reynolds number, assuming Ô¨Åxed geometry, corresponds to an increase in the Ô¨Çuid viscosity. If (situation B) at Ô¨Åxed
geometry, we intend to keep the viscosity Ô¨Åxed, i.e., keep the physical properties of the Ô¨Çuid Ô¨Åxed, then a reduction in
Re has to be accompanied with a reduction in the Ô¨Çow rate with the same factor. The two situations A and B will be
presented next.
We investigated the evolution of the pressure drop and the shear stress for situation A, i.e., the Ô¨Åxed Ô¨Çow rate
situation. The eÔ¨Äect of pulsatility is stronger at lower Re, i.e., in case the Ô¨Çuid is more viscous. To maintain a given
Ô¨Çow rate while increasing the viscosity, we observed that the pressure drop needs to be increased. In Figure 7(a) the
shear stress levels are seen to increase with increasing viscosity. This response is in stark contrast with situation B in
which we vary the Reynolds number, while keeping the viscosity of the Ô¨Çuid and the geometry Ô¨Åxed. In situation B we
noticed that a reduction of the Reynolds number, i.e., a slower Ô¨Çow, implies a reduction in the pressure drop over the
domain. The shear stress levels are seen to be lower when the Reynolds number is reduced (Figure 7(b). Not only the
level but also the complexity of the shear stress response is considerably diminished with reduced Reynolds number.
All these Ô¨Åndings correspond directly with physical intuition, illustrating the qualitative reliability of the simulations.

