5. Conclusions
In this paper we presented a basic immersed boundary method (IB) for the prediction of pulsatile viscous Ô¨Çow in
models for cerebral aneurysms. Applications of this method to simple model geometries such as a curved vessel and a
model aneurysm were presented. The Ô¨Çow was simulated successfully using the IB approach. Complex Ô¨Çow structures
were observed at Re = 500, displaying a signiÔ¨Åcant Ô¨Çow separation inside the spherical cavity and complex, intrinsic
Ô¨Çow dynamics that is not very sensitive to external Ô¨Çow rate variations. Such would correspond to an aneurysm that
developed into a considerable size in which the Ô¨Çow response is somewhat disconnected from the bodily rhythms.
The pressure drop across the domain was found to reÔ¨Çect the periodic forcing much more clearly, even at high Re.
The shear stress on the vessel and aneurysm walls was computed as well. At high Re a highly irregular, rapidly
varying shear stress development was recorded, which could possibly induce an acceleration in the development of
the aneurysm in its Ô¨Ånal stages. In order to extract more reliably such general information of clinical relevance, more
research is needed into the reliability of the simulation results.
We showed the application of the IB method for a range of Ô¨Çow conditions and pulsatile forcing. Changes in the
amplitude of the pulsatile Ô¨Çow do not seem to generate qualitative diÔ¨Äerence - rather an increase in the forcing amplitude leads to a corresponding increase in pressure drop and shear stress. Conversely, changes in the Ô¨Çow conditions
can give rise to strong qualitative diÔ¨Äerences. We investigated two, physically diÔ¨Äerent situations. Keeping the scale
of the problem Ô¨Åxed we compared results at diÔ¨Äerent viscosity, keeping the Ô¨Çow rate Ô¨Åxed, and results at diÔ¨Äerent
Ô¨Çow rate, keeping the viscosity Ô¨Åxed. The latter situation corresponds most closely to actual physiological conditions
in which a higher Ô¨Çow rate, i.e., higher Reynolds number, requires a higher pressure drop, giving rise to higher shear
stresses and considerably more complex Ô¨Çow development in terms of vortical structures and shear stress maxima. In
case the viscosity is varied at Ô¨Åxed Ô¨Çow rate we observed the more unusual situation of an increased pressure drop
and shear stress in case of a lower Reynolds number. This is solely due to the requirement of generating a Ô¨Åxed
mass Ô¨Çow for an ever more viscous Ô¨Çuid. In each of these cases the IB method readily provided the qualitative Ô¨Çow
consequences, even at rather coarse resolutions.
The application of computational support in the monitoring and treatment of cerebral aneurysms is a Ô¨Åeld of
ongoing research. The location, time-dependence and intensity of peaks in the shear stress are all of relevance to
medical practice, as these appear to be related to the long-time evolution of the condition of vessel walls. In order to
achieve a closer connection with medical practice several steps need to be taken. A central element is the incorporation
of realistic patient aneurysms and their coupling to proper inÔ¨Çow and outÔ¨Çow conditions. As illustrated in this paper,

